[Claude]: The dataflow is confirmed. Now I have all the information needed to submit the finding. Let me summarize the vulnerability:

**Complete attack chain:**
1. HTTP request path from `theRequest.getPathInfo()` (line 181) — fully attacker-controlled
2. Only check: `requestPath.startsWith("/swagger-ui/")` (line 200/206) — bypassable with `..` sequences
3. `resourcePath = requestPath.substring("/swagger-ui/".length())` (line 246) — strips prefix, leaves `../../etc...`
4. `ClasspathUtil.loadResourceAsStream("/META-INF/resources/webjars/swagger-ui/" + mySwaggerUiVersion + "/" + resourcePath)` (line 247) — directly loads the user-controlled path as a classpath resource
5. No `..` check, no canonicalization, no deny-list
6. **Constraint**: Only served if path ends in `.js`, `.map`, `.css`, or `.html` — but many sensitive classpath resources could have these extensions, or be located next to resources with such names. More critically, the classpath traversal allows reading any classpath resource whose path ends with an allowed extension.

**Concrete bypass**: `GET /swagger-ui/../../WEB-INF/applicationContext.css` → `resourcePath = "../../WEB-INF/applicationContext.css"` → loads classpath resource at `/META-INF/resources/webjars/swagger-ui/<version>/../../WEB-INF/applicationContext.css` which resolves to `/META-INF/resources/webjars/WEB-INF/applicationContext.css` (or further if more `..` are used). An attacker could exfiltrate classpath resources that have `.js`/`.css`/`.html` extensions.

